snippet.textDisplay: I wonder how much the prep really matters. It'd be fun to blind taste test the finicky ones and see if they really end up preferring and being able to identify their exact style versus different amounts and water temp. I think it comes down to the beans and the rest doesn't matter as much. There's a wide range where good beans taste good. I've had fancy coffee shop coffee and wasn't blown away, and I've gone full nerd with fresh grind by hand every morning with a mortar and pestle, aeropress, french press, drip, espresso, all sorts of good beans. It all changes the character of the coffee, no doubt, but I still think the actual bean is the most significant factor, not preparation. As long as you get your ratios within a reasonable window it's all good. I aim for strong because it's easy to water down but not easy to make weak coffee better. Pretty much, only high quality freeze dried can do that in a reasonable amount of time. Otherwise you'd have to make super strong coffee and add it to the weak batch.
